{"id":"1707.05369","submitter":"Tiberiu Harko","authors":"J. A. Belinchon, T. Harko, M. K. Mak","title":"Approximate Analytical Solution for the Dynamic Model of Large Amplitude\n  Non-Linear Oscillations Arising in Structural Engineering","comments":"8 pages, 1 figure, accepted for publication in Journal of Applied\n  Mathematics and Engineering","journal-ref":"Journal of Applied Mathematics and Engineering Vol 8 (2016) Part\n  I, pages 25-34","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this work we obtain an approximate solution of the strongly nonlinear\nsecond order differential equation $\\frac{d^{2}u}{dt^{2}}+\\omega ^{2}u+\\alpha\nu^{2}\\frac{d^{2}u}{dt^{2}}+\\alpha u\\left( \\frac{du}{dt}\\right)^{2}+\\beta \\omega\n^{2}u^{3}=0$, describing the large amplitude free vibrations of a uniform\ncantilever beam, by using a method based on the Laplace transform, and the\nconvolution theorem. By reformulating the initial differential equation as an\nintegral equation, with the use of an iterative procedure, an approximate\nsolution of the nonlinear vibration equation can be obtained in any order of\napproximation. The iterative approximate solutions are compared with the exact\nnumerical solution of the vibration equation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 25 Jun 2017 14:27:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-07-19"}
{"id":"1707.08441","submitter":"Petro Mchedlov-Petrosyan","authors":"Petro Mchedlov-Petrosyan, Leonid Davydov","title":"Exact travelling wave solutions for the Penrose-Fife Phase Field Model","comments":"15 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.mtrl-sci cond-mat.other","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Penrose-Fife Phase Field Model is now a well-established model in the\ntheory of phase transitions. In the course of study of this model both the\nrigorous mathematical results and approximate solutions were obtained. However,\nto the best of our knowledge, no exact solutions were given in the literature.\nIn the present paper we give exact traveling wave solutions for this system.\nWhile the functional form of the solutions is rather simple, the dependence of\nsolutions on the parameters of the model is quite complicated.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 25 Jun 2017 15:31:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-07-27"}
